00:00:25.936 --> 00:00:31.470
PROFESSOR: A lot of what we
have done, until today, we

00:00:31.470 --> 00:00:40.840
sort of assumed, at one place
or another, that the people

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:42.640
were unable to borrow.

00:00:42.640 --> 00:00:45.230
For example, a lot of the
s-shaped problem that we have

00:00:45.230 --> 00:00:48.710
seen along the way, people would
be able to escape from

00:00:48.710 --> 00:00:50.850
them if only they
could borrow.

00:00:50.850 --> 00:00:53.740
For example, all of the issues
on risk that we've discussed,

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:58.220
that people have these shocks
and they lose their business.

00:00:58.220 --> 00:01:01.170
And that puts them back on the
left part of the curve.

00:01:01.170 --> 00:01:06.080
This could be removed if you
were able to borrow your way

00:01:06.080 --> 00:01:07.890
out of these problems.

00:01:07.890 --> 00:01:09.700
So when you are in a bad
shock, you borrow.

00:01:09.700 --> 00:01:12.180
And when you are in good state,
you reimburse, and

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:13.430
everything is good.

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:22.790
So it seems that we needed to
spend some time discussing.

00:01:22.790 --> 00:01:24.190
We can't really take
it as given that

00:01:24.190 --> 00:01:26.090
people can't borrow.

00:01:26.090 --> 00:01:27.490
First, because it's not
true, actually.

00:01:27.490 --> 00:01:29.300
Poor people borrow a lot.

00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:30.900
It depends, a bit, from
country to country.

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:34.270
But in a country like India,
for example, about 70% of

00:01:34.270 --> 00:01:37.530
people will have some loan from
someone, usually not from

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:42.330
a bank, but from a moneylender
or a shopkeeper or their

00:01:42.330 --> 00:01:44.210
landlord or something
like that.

00:01:44.210 --> 00:01:47.180
So there are actually a lot
of lending-borrowing

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:49.030
relationships around.

00:01:49.030 --> 00:01:51.500
So it doesn't seem to be a very
good assumption to start

00:01:51.500 --> 00:01:53.830
with the idea that people
can't borrow.

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:56.810
Secondly is, even if they
couldn't borrow, we want to

00:01:56.810 --> 00:01:58.740
spend some time and
try to understand

00:01:58.740 --> 00:02:00.490
why that's the case.

00:02:00.490 --> 00:02:06.660
So in a sense, we could have
done this many lectures ago.

00:02:06.660 --> 00:02:12.360
But finally, we are now getting
the crux of this

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.610
borrowing question.

00:02:15.610 --> 00:02:21.070
What the newspaper article, for
today, made kind of clear

00:02:21.070 --> 00:02:25.970
is that this is one way, one
reason why you should be

00:02:25.970 --> 00:02:28.320
interested in these things or
you might be interested in

00:02:28.320 --> 00:02:29.570
this things.

00:02:33.490 --> 00:02:39.040
Microcredit is being discussed
a lot these days.

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:43.190
Has anyone heard what is
happening to Yunus these days?

00:02:43.190 --> 00:02:46.075
Have any of you heard like
what's the situation?

00:02:50.550 --> 00:02:50.916
Sorry?

00:02:50.916 --> 00:02:51.850
AUDIENCE: Did you say, Yunus?

00:02:51.850 --> 00:02:52.450
PROFESSOR: Yunus, yeah.

00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:53.856
What's happening with Yunus?

00:02:53.856 --> 00:02:56.172
AUDIENCE: I don't know the
details, but he's kind of

00:02:56.172 --> 00:02:58.587
getting pushed out of the
organization that he started,

00:02:58.587 --> 00:03:02.460
Grameen, the microfinance
banking [INAUDIBLE].

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:05.750
PROFESSOR: Right, so he's being
pushed out of Grameen on

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:06.700
sort of technical reasons.

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:07.540
I mean it's not.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:09.540
He is older than 70.

00:03:09.540 --> 00:03:12.170
And then the government is
arguing that Grameen is a

00:03:12.170 --> 00:03:16.320
public bank, because
the state owns some

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:17.370
parts of the capital.

00:03:17.370 --> 00:03:19.120
But a very small part,
because Grameen is

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:21.446
largely held by the borrowers.

00:03:21.446 --> 00:03:23.700
They're now trying
to push him out.

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:25.940
And at the same time, there is
a discourse along the line

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:29.030
that, ooh, maybe microcredit is
not all that its cracked up

00:03:29.030 --> 00:03:31.010
to be, et cetera.

00:03:31.010 --> 00:03:40.870
This follows a big event in
India, in November, where, in

00:03:40.870 --> 00:03:44.980
Andhra Pradesh, one of the hot
beds of microfinance in India,

00:03:44.980 --> 00:03:48.730
the government decided that
it was now illegal to--

00:03:48.730 --> 00:03:51.440
issued and ordinance saying
that it was illegal to ask

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:56.210
people to repay in the absence
of the local mayor.

00:03:56.210 --> 00:04:01.120
So given that the local mayor
are not always in the field,

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:04.120
always present, et cetera, that
turns out to be a pretty

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:05.420
big constraint.

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:08.590
So all the repayments stopped
to microfinance agencies in

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:09.710
Andhra Pradesh, in November.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:12.460
And to this day, they haven't
really restarted.

00:04:12.460 --> 00:04:15.320
And in the context of that, you
have had a lot of articles

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:19.149
in the press about maybe
microcredit is actually bad,

00:04:19.149 --> 00:04:21.300
maybe microcredit is
the new usury.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:23.980
But I don't want to go into the
details of whether it's

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:28.380
good or bad now, because you're
going to do it in the

00:04:28.380 --> 00:04:30.140
next lecture.

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:33.500
What I want to do is to give
us some tools, today.

00:04:33.500 --> 00:04:36.350
So it's going to be a little bit
more theoretical lecture

00:04:36.350 --> 00:04:37.460
than usually.

00:04:37.460 --> 00:04:42.920
I want to give us some tools
to try to understand why it

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:46.300
might be difficult for the poor
to borrow, why the poor

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:51.460
might face higher interest
rates, and what microcredit

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:55.750
has done that can partially
solve this program or why it

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:57.460
doesn't solve them
fully, et cetera.

00:04:57.460 --> 00:05:01.282
That's kind of where
we're heading, now.

00:05:01.282 --> 00:05:04.770
So maybe we can start with some
facts that it's good to

00:05:04.770 --> 00:05:05.550
have in mind.

00:05:05.550 --> 00:05:08.820
And then we are going to have a
series of simple models that

00:05:08.820 --> 00:05:10.790
we are going to try to
apply to these facts.

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:17.730
So the first fact is that most
of the poor do not have access

00:05:17.730 --> 00:05:23.690
to any kind of formal credit,
excluding microfinance, which

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:27.150
reaches about 200 million
people worldwide.

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:31.480
So most of the poor don't borrow
from a bank or from a

00:05:31.480 --> 00:05:34.010
credit union or something
like that.

00:05:34.010 --> 00:05:37.360
There are some numbers that are
coming from the the data

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:40.520
set on the life of the
poor, under $1 a day.

00:05:40.520 --> 00:05:42.470
You see, on the left side,
the fraction of

00:05:42.470 --> 00:05:43.480
people who have a loan.

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:46.570
And you see that it's
not nothing.

00:05:46.570 --> 00:05:51.110
Actually, the number
six is wrong.

00:05:51.110 --> 00:05:51.520
It's more.

00:05:51.520 --> 00:05:57.350
60% of people had a loan in
India, Cote d'Ivoire, 31%, 12%

00:05:57.350 --> 00:06:00.375
in Indonesia, 93% in Pakistan.

00:06:00.375 --> 00:06:00.710
Yeah?

00:06:00.710 --> 00:06:03.410
AUDIENCE: Why is there is such
a big discrepancy between--

00:06:03.410 --> 00:06:04.770
or why [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:04.770 --> 00:06:08.260
informal market in Pakistan?

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:11.275
PROFESSOR: So first, what
you notice is that

00:06:11.275 --> 00:06:13.780
everywhere you have.

00:06:13.780 --> 00:06:16.840
The fact that a lot of the
loans that people.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:19.070
So there are two facts in this
corner-- or three facts.

00:06:19.070 --> 00:06:22.460
One is that it is not that
credit access is 0 in most

00:06:22.460 --> 00:06:26.110
countries, except in Panama,
where it's pretty low.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:30.130
The second fact is maybe what
you were talking about, that

00:06:30.130 --> 00:06:33.220
there is a lot of viability,
where in a place like Pakistan

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:36.000
or India-- once the typo
is corrected--

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.130
you have an enormous amount of
lending, like 93% of people

00:06:41.130 --> 00:06:42.830
have a loan.

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:46.000
And the third fact is that these
loans are mostly not

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:50.330
from the formal sector, with
the possible exception of

00:06:50.330 --> 00:06:57.520
Indonesia, that has 25%
of loans coming

00:06:57.520 --> 00:06:58.980
from the formal sector.

00:06:58.980 --> 00:07:00.660
Do you want to re-ask your
question to make sure then?

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:03.436
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I mean, just
Pakistan has such percentage

00:07:03.436 --> 00:07:05.121
of individual with loans.

00:07:05.121 --> 00:07:09.504
I mean it would be more
understandable that fraction

00:07:09.504 --> 00:07:11.939
of loans coming from a bank in
a country that doesn't have

00:07:11.939 --> 00:07:13.400
that much lending would be
lower, just because there

00:07:13.400 --> 00:07:14.390
isn't that much opportunity.

00:07:14.390 --> 00:07:17.324
What surprises me is how low the
fraction of loans that are

00:07:17.324 --> 00:07:19.565
coming from a bank, given
how many individuals

00:07:19.565 --> 00:07:20.810
have loans at all.

00:07:20.810 --> 00:07:23.798
So I was wondering if there is
a reason that that's the case

00:07:23.798 --> 00:07:26.860
in Pakistan or is
it an anomaly?

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:28.500
PROFESSOR: So in a sense,
we could ask the

00:07:28.500 --> 00:07:30.710
question two ways.

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:34.480
Why is the informal loan market
so particularly active

00:07:34.480 --> 00:07:35.830
in Pakistan?

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:39.920
Or why is the formal
market so absent?

00:07:39.920 --> 00:07:42.230
And I think the first question,
in a sense, is the

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:43.790
way to ask it.

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:46.730
Basically, in Pakistan, there
is not much more formal

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:53.080
lending then in a place like,
say, Cote d'Ivoire.

00:07:53.080 --> 00:07:57.620
But there is much more informal
lending, so there is

00:07:57.620 --> 00:07:58.420
much more activity.

00:07:58.420 --> 00:07:59.820
That varies a lot.

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:01.520
That varies from country
to country.

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:04.480
Within countries, it also varies
from place to place.

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:10.120
And it also varies even within
a village, within a region.

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:12.710
Who has access to credit, who
doesn't have access to credit

00:08:12.710 --> 00:08:14.080
also varies.

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:18.000
So I can't really answer the
question, right now.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.270
But I'm sort of hoping that,
by the end of the lecture,

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:23.520
we'll have some elements that
we can apply back to saying,

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:25.252
why are things different
in Pakistan ?

00:08:25.252 --> 00:08:25.590
Yeah?

00:08:25.590 --> 00:08:28.824
AUDIENCE: What's the percent
of people with a loan

00:08:28.824 --> 00:08:30.680
[INAUDIBLE] in developed
countries?

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:32.434
PROFESSOR: What's the percentage
of people with a

00:08:32.434 --> 00:08:33.760
loan in developed countries?

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:36.059
I think it would be very,
very, very high.

00:08:36.059 --> 00:08:40.010
Because, as soon as you have a
credit card, you have a loan.

00:08:40.010 --> 00:08:43.230
So I think, as a fraction of
adults, that it would be

00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:45.210
pretty close to one,
I would say.

00:08:49.070 --> 00:08:50.330
You're absolutely right.

00:08:50.330 --> 00:08:51.630
I don't know if this is
what you had in mind.

00:08:51.630 --> 00:08:55.840
But this is lower than in
developed countries.

00:08:55.840 --> 00:09:00.210
And what is particularly
striking is the low access to

00:09:00.210 --> 00:09:03.875
any kind of formal lending.

00:09:03.875 --> 00:09:06.845
AUDIENCE: How would it look
different if it was urban

00:09:06.845 --> 00:09:07.835
instead of rural households?

00:09:07.835 --> 00:09:09.815
Because like Panama
is really weird.

00:09:09.815 --> 00:09:11.810
It must be [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:11.810 --> 00:09:13.060
PROFESSOR: Few people
living [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:15.620 --> 00:09:19.350
In the same table, we also have
the urban households.

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:25.140
They will have more loans
and more informal loans.

00:09:25.140 --> 00:09:29.710
So the ratio of informal to
formal in urban households is

00:09:29.710 --> 00:09:32.410
actually not that different
from what it is here.

00:09:32.410 --> 00:09:35.150
You have more loans and more
informal loans and more formal

00:09:35.150 --> 00:09:37.000
loans, with a ratio--

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:37.670
to my knowledge--

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:40.590
remaining more or
less constant.

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:44.930
That's the first fact, a fair
amount of loans but very few

00:09:44.930 --> 00:09:47.780
formal loans.

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:52.030
The second fact is more
like a history fact.

00:09:52.030 --> 00:09:53.880
Governments have tried,
historically, to do

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:55.680
something about it.

00:09:55.680 --> 00:10:01.000
So in the 1960s and the 1970s,
many governments of developing

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:07.540
countries, in India, in Brazil,
in Colombia, in Peru,

00:10:07.540 --> 00:10:14.660
in Mexico tried to either force
or subsidize the banks,

00:10:14.660 --> 00:10:19.650
either public banks or
government banks, to go and

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:21.150
lend to the poor.

00:10:21.150 --> 00:10:25.400
So in India, for example, the
way it happened is, first, the

00:10:25.400 --> 00:10:29.700
banks were nationalized, by Mrs.
Gandhi, during the same

00:10:29.700 --> 00:10:30.625
period as The Emergency.

00:10:30.625 --> 00:10:33.470
They were nationalized
in two waves.

00:10:33.470 --> 00:10:36.780
And then the banks, irrespective
of whether they

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:40.580
were nationalized or not, were
then told that they could not

00:10:40.580 --> 00:10:45.390
open a branch in a town if they
did not open, at the same

00:10:45.390 --> 00:10:48.730
time, four branches in
rural areas that were

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:50.430
not previously served.

00:10:50.430 --> 00:10:53.900
So as the bank tried to expand
in an urban area, where they

00:10:53.900 --> 00:10:58.250
had a market, they had to
expand in rural areas.

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:03.810
And moreover, to this day, banks
were given rules about

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:07.190
how their portfolio needed
to be allocated.

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:11.350
So you have a rule called a
priority sector rule, saying

00:11:11.350 --> 00:11:15.600
that the bank must lend 40%
of their portfolio to the

00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.260
priority sector.

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:19.040
The priority sector is
small enterprises

00:11:19.040 --> 00:11:20.420
in the rural sector.

00:11:20.420 --> 00:11:23.180
And within priority sector,
they need to do at least a

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:25.190
fraction to the rural sector.

00:11:25.190 --> 00:11:27.510
So both of these things are
forcing the banks to go into

00:11:27.510 --> 00:11:31.610
the rural areas and then forcing
them to balance their

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:35.900
portfolio this way and capping
the interest rate up, capping

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:37.670
the interest rate that
they could charge.

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:41.350
It had the result that loans
were pushed to farmers and

00:11:41.350 --> 00:11:42.860
things like that.

00:11:42.860 --> 00:11:48.640
But those loans were rather a
disaster, with very, very high

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:49.910
default rates.

00:11:49.910 --> 00:11:52.120
So a lot of people never
reimbursed their loans.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:54.930
And eventually, they became more
like a political giveaway

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.980
rather than a credit program.

00:11:56.980 --> 00:12:00.020
So it became sort of expensive,
inefficient way to

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:04.420
give people money as opposed
to a real credit program.

00:12:04.420 --> 00:12:06.570
Let's give you one illustration
of a political

00:12:06.570 --> 00:12:11.650
giveaway, which is a paper by
Shawn Cole, which looks at

00:12:11.650 --> 00:12:14.050
what he calls lending cycle.

00:12:14.050 --> 00:12:16.970
You're missing something
important, which is what is on

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:21.900
the x-axis, over here, is the
year until the next election.

00:12:21.900 --> 00:12:23.952
So this is the year.

00:12:23.952 --> 00:12:26.460
There is an election about
every five years.

00:12:26.460 --> 00:12:27.870
So this is saying this
is the year just

00:12:27.870 --> 00:12:30.730
before the next election.

00:12:30.730 --> 00:12:34.280
And what you're seeing is that
the year before an election,

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:37.780
you get a huge boost in
lending, suddenly.

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:40.050
And this is for public banks.

00:12:40.050 --> 00:12:42.550
And if we look at private
banks-- there are a few left--

00:12:42.550 --> 00:12:45.830
you don't have these political
lending cycle.

00:12:45.830 --> 00:12:48.410
And another thing that he has,
which is interesting, is that

00:12:48.410 --> 00:12:51.940
you get more of this boost in
swing districts, in districts

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:54.670
that are where the margin of
victory in the previous

00:12:54.670 --> 00:12:59.980
election was low, then in safe
districts, where it's pretty

00:12:59.980 --> 00:13:01.845
clear who was going to
win the election.

00:13:01.845 --> 00:13:02.180
Yeah?

00:13:02.180 --> 00:13:03.380
AUDIENCE: I might
have missed it.

00:13:03.380 --> 00:13:06.321
So why is there more lending
before an election?

00:13:06.321 --> 00:13:09.123
Is that because after the person
gets elected, everyone

00:13:09.123 --> 00:13:10.060
just defaults [INAUDIBLE]?

00:13:10.060 --> 00:13:13.590
PROFESSOR: So remember all of
the facts that I just said.

00:13:13.590 --> 00:13:16.090
You get more lending just
before the election.

00:13:16.090 --> 00:13:17.450
It's only public banks.

00:13:17.450 --> 00:13:20.280
And it's only in swing
districts, in districts where

00:13:20.280 --> 00:13:23.010
the margin of victory in the
previous election was close.

00:13:23.010 --> 00:13:25.212
So why do they lend more?

00:13:25.212 --> 00:13:27.180
AUDIENCE: They borrow
[INAUDIBLE], because the

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:29.640
candidates will make a promise
that they'll [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:29.640 --> 00:13:32.600
don't have to pay [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:32.600 --> 00:13:34.720
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:36.160
The default rate is
so high that loans

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:39.675
are pretty much gifts.

00:13:39.675 --> 00:13:43.105
So if you give more of it, than
it's like vote buying

00:13:43.105 --> 00:13:45.180
kind of activities.

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:45.620
Yeah?

00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:46.500
AUDIENCE: Could you
go back to the

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:48.320
previous slide for a second?

00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:51.940
Why is it 0, negative
0.1, negative 0.2?

00:13:51.940 --> 00:13:55.415
PROFESSOR: So 0 is just
a normalization.

00:13:55.415 --> 00:13:56.755
So it starts at 0.

00:13:56.755 --> 00:13:58.940
It is saying that any year that
is not a year just before

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:02.560
the election is below.

00:14:02.560 --> 00:14:06.620
Because this is to show, in
relation to that year, the old

00:14:06.620 --> 00:14:07.320
one is negative.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:09.705
An you have the little
standard errors on

00:14:09.705 --> 00:14:11.660
the side, as well.

00:14:11.660 --> 00:14:13.330
Good question.

00:14:13.330 --> 00:14:17.540
Whatever the level is,
he's normalized them.

00:14:17.540 --> 00:14:20.850
So basically, that is telling
you that even

00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:22.180
if you had the effort.

00:14:22.180 --> 00:14:24.190
It's not that Grameen's
didn't try.

00:14:24.190 --> 00:14:25.870
But in India--

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:28.340
and then it's also the case
in other countries--

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:32.290
eventually, they stopped trying
to at least use these

00:14:32.290 --> 00:14:34.170
banks as banks.

00:14:34.170 --> 00:14:36.410
They are more used as like
pushing money away.

00:14:36.410 --> 00:14:39.240
Eventually, in India, they
decided to shut down the

00:14:39.240 --> 00:14:42.750
social banking program
in the early 1990s.

00:14:42.750 --> 00:14:46.600
Now the banks that don't have
to start in rural areas.

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:48.940
They still have the priority
sector rules, but they don't

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:51.290
have to start in rural areas.

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:57.650
So that's the fast fact of two
halves of a fact, very little

00:14:57.650 --> 00:15:06.420
formal lending and rather not
very good performances in the

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:09.620
effort to lend to the poor.

00:15:09.620 --> 00:15:14.730
The second fact, so people, when
they access loans, access

00:15:14.730 --> 00:15:18.230
them mostly from the
informal sector.

00:15:18.230 --> 00:15:22.180
And the second fact that is
important is that loans are

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:24.570
available in the informal
sector, but the interest rates

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:29.770
are very high, very high and
very variable, which is going

00:15:29.770 --> 00:15:31.330
to be our next fact.

00:15:31.330 --> 00:15:36.140
But just to say very high, the
sort of range where I think

00:15:36.140 --> 00:15:40.620
you would get most of the rates
is between 40% a year to

00:15:40.620 --> 00:15:42.670
200% a year.

00:15:42.670 --> 00:15:48.400
That's pretty high, if you
compare very, very high

00:15:48.400 --> 00:15:51.130
interest rates on your credit
card, in the US, is of the

00:15:51.130 --> 00:15:52.710
order of maybe 20% a year.

00:15:52.710 --> 00:15:53.510
Yeah?

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:55.040
AUDIENCE: So a question I had
while reading the article was,

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:56.984
yes, they're very high,
percentage-wise.

00:15:56.984 --> 00:16:01.170
But if the loan amounts are so
small, like, say, if I were to

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:03.630
borrow $1 today, I have
to pay $2 tomorrow.

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:06.525
That's a huge percent increase,
but it's not that

00:16:06.525 --> 00:16:08.640
big of an amount.

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:11.197
PROFESSOR: It's not that big
of an amount but from your

00:16:11.197 --> 00:16:12.510
perspective.

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:14.770
It's a very good point.

00:16:14.770 --> 00:16:17.480
And we're going to go back to
that, which is the fact that

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:22.190
it's not that big of an amount
is relevant for the bank, who

00:16:22.190 --> 00:16:24.355
is giving you this money.

00:16:24.355 --> 00:16:26.930
But for you, it just means
that whatever--

00:16:26.930 --> 00:16:29.520
it's still, the interest
rate is very high.

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:33.470
So unless you have a very good
use for this money, the fact

00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:36.470
that it's just $1, yet you have
somehow to find a way to

00:16:36.470 --> 00:16:38.900
transform this $1 into
$2 next year.

00:16:42.370 --> 00:16:43.800
We're going to go back
to your point.

00:16:43.800 --> 00:16:45.340
From the point of view
of supply, it's

00:16:45.340 --> 00:16:46.910
going to matter a lot.

00:16:46.910 --> 00:16:47.590
You're going to see that.

00:16:47.590 --> 00:16:49.970
It's going to turn out to be one
of the key things, which

00:16:49.970 --> 00:16:53.230
is, because people borrow a lot,
these high interest rates

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:56.090
are, in a month, a relatively
small part.

00:16:56.090 --> 00:16:59.370
But from the point of view of
the borrower, it means that,

00:16:59.370 --> 00:17:02.130
not only they can't borrow much,
but they have to repay

00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:04.349
this huge interest rate.

00:17:04.349 --> 00:17:06.440
It comes to the daily rate.

00:17:06.440 --> 00:17:08.520
Some people borrow on
the daily market.

00:17:08.520 --> 00:17:13.260
For example, food vendors borrow
on the daily market.

00:17:13.260 --> 00:17:17.839
A common rate on the daily
market is 5% a day.

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:21.740
So do you have like a guess of
what 5% a day is per year?

00:17:25.150 --> 00:17:26.887
An order of magnitude?

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:35.870
Is it 5% multiplied by 365?

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:36.272
AUDIENCE: No.

00:17:36.272 --> 00:17:37.076
Because it's compounded.

00:17:37.076 --> 00:17:39.900
PROFESSOR: No, because
it compounds.

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:45.180
So if it's on the order of the
millions of percentage, it's a

00:17:45.180 --> 00:17:47.780
very, very, very, very, high
interest rate, because it

00:17:47.780 --> 00:17:49.270
compounds it really fast.

00:17:49.270 --> 00:17:53.400
It's 1.05 to the power of 365.

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.500
It's a huge interest rate.

00:17:55.500 --> 00:18:01.020
That's on the high range
but not uncommon.

00:18:01.020 --> 00:18:03.340
There is one study that
I'm going to keep

00:18:03.340 --> 00:18:04.820
returning to, today.

00:18:04.820 --> 00:18:10.590
It's a lovely study on Pakistan,
where some guy,

00:18:10.590 --> 00:18:13.725
called Aleem, went and talked
to various moneylenders and

00:18:13.725 --> 00:18:16.390
collected very detailed data
on their operation.

00:18:16.390 --> 00:18:20.130
And for Pakistan, he found that
the interest they charge

00:18:20.130 --> 00:18:23.750
was 79%, almost.

00:18:23.750 --> 00:18:26.020
And you could say, well,
this is because their

00:18:26.020 --> 00:18:28.030
own money is expensive.

00:18:28.030 --> 00:18:31.810
But they're own cost
of capital is 33%.

00:18:31.810 --> 00:18:33.730
So their own money is expensive,
because they are

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:35.920
probably borrowing from the
bank or borrowing from

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:37.730
somewhere at some high cost.

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:41.260
But there's still a big wedge
between the cost of capital,

00:18:41.260 --> 00:18:44.000
for them, and what they
charge the lender.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:44.870
So that's fact two.

00:18:44.870 --> 00:18:48.600
Keep in mind, high
interest rate.

00:18:48.600 --> 00:18:51.020
Fact three is these interest
rates are not only high,

00:18:51.020 --> 00:18:56.990
they're very variable, even
within the same village.

00:18:56.990 --> 00:19:05.160
So if you go back to the Aleem
study, the mean was 79%.

00:19:05.160 --> 00:19:09.090
The standard deviation is 38%.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:14.740
Which means that the 95%
confidence interval includes a

00:19:14.740 --> 00:19:18.590
very low number, like 2%
a year, and a very high

00:19:18.590 --> 00:19:20.460
number, like 150%.

00:19:20.460 --> 00:19:24.060
So it means you see, pretty
frequently, in the same

00:19:24.060 --> 00:19:28.990
village, people borrowing at
very, very different traits.

00:19:28.990 --> 00:19:31.720
So that is a certain other fact
we have to have in mind.

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:32.205
Yeah?

00:19:32.205 --> 00:19:35.115
AUDIENCE: Was that huge range,
is that a reflection, then,

00:19:35.115 --> 00:19:38.510
that lenders are really adept
at calculating, precisely,

00:19:38.510 --> 00:19:42.390
someone's actual likelihood
of repayment or is that

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:42.875
favoritism?

00:19:42.875 --> 00:19:43.845
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

00:19:43.845 --> 00:19:45.800
So we'd have to understand
like how come

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:47.050
this can be so variable?

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:52.930
Is it likely that the likelihood
of repayment can

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:54.970
explain such a big range
or do we have to

00:19:54.970 --> 00:19:56.680
think about other things?

00:19:56.680 --> 00:19:58.970
And if it's where the likelihood
of repayment, can

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.220
it explain that much
difference?

00:20:01.220 --> 00:20:04.590
AUDIENCE: Is this taking into
account the fact that if the

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:07.484
lender had a spell, then he
gets paid more, because he

00:20:07.484 --> 00:20:10.820
needs more money?

00:20:10.820 --> 00:20:11.670
PROFESSOR: No.

00:20:11.670 --> 00:20:13.980
That's the average rate
that they charge.

00:20:16.870 --> 00:20:18.850
These are really moneylenders,
like professional

00:20:18.850 --> 00:20:19.120
moneylenders.

00:20:19.120 --> 00:20:25.280
So I think what you're referring
to is, sometimes,

00:20:25.280 --> 00:20:28.460
when people lend to each other,
say, you know, you and

00:20:28.460 --> 00:20:29.710
I lend to each other.

00:20:29.710 --> 00:20:31.770
Because you have had a bad time,
I lend you some money.

00:20:31.770 --> 00:20:33.860
And then when I get better, you
lend me some money when

00:20:33.860 --> 00:20:35.550
you get better.

00:20:35.550 --> 00:20:39.160
When you see people doing that
informally, what you're seeing

00:20:39.160 --> 00:20:42.590
is that people tend to pay
higher interest rate when

00:20:42.590 --> 00:20:45.830
they're doing well and lower
when they're doing poorly.

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:51.950
But also, they tend to pay
higher interest rates when the

00:20:51.950 --> 00:20:56.220
people who have lent them
money are doing poorly.

00:20:56.220 --> 00:21:00.760
And they pay higher interest
rate when the lender is doing

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:04.080
poorly and lower interest rate
when the lender is doing well.

00:21:04.080 --> 00:21:06.930
So the former could be just,
because I don't have money, I

00:21:06.930 --> 00:21:08.000
can't reimburse.

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.250
The latter is a sign that people
sometimes use this

00:21:12.250 --> 00:21:15.370
informal lending between each
other as a way of smoothing

00:21:15.370 --> 00:21:16.620
consumption.

00:21:19.030 --> 00:21:19.940
So we can remove that.

00:21:19.940 --> 00:21:23.710
These are more like a way of
insuring, mutually insuring,

00:21:23.710 --> 00:21:25.420
like you saw in the
last few lectures.

00:21:25.420 --> 00:21:27.810
Where these are like
professional moneylenders that

00:21:27.810 --> 00:21:29.690
are charging different rates.

00:21:29.690 --> 00:21:33.140
So maybe we need to go back
to your question.

00:21:33.140 --> 00:21:38.580
Is it the case that that can be
explained by the ability to

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:41.340
repay or do we need to bring
in some more things, like

00:21:41.340 --> 00:21:45.240
favoritism, social
relationships, what have you?

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:46.300
So let's keep that in mind.

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:52.230
We now have three, very little
formal lending, high interest

00:21:52.230 --> 00:21:55.316
rates, very variable
interest rates.

00:21:55.316 --> 00:22:01.110
The fourth fact, one of the
dimension of variation is how

00:22:01.110 --> 00:22:02.990
rich you are.

00:22:02.990 --> 00:22:07.850
So the rich have larger loans,
and they pay lower rates.

00:22:07.850 --> 00:22:17.015
So here's one fact for all of
India showing that the range

00:22:17.015 --> 00:22:22.645
for the landless is between 28%
and 125% interest rate, so

00:22:22.645 --> 00:22:25.630
again, this wide range with a
pretty high interest rate.

00:22:25.630 --> 00:22:28.840
And the range for the people
who have land is

00:22:28.840 --> 00:22:31.530
between 21% and 40%.

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:34.510
So its both a smaller range,
and it doesn't include the

00:22:34.510 --> 00:22:36.320
very high value.

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:38.990
So the rich tend to pay-- and
is this is just one fact.

00:22:38.990 --> 00:22:42.800
But we can accumulate
these facts.

00:22:42.800 --> 00:22:45.310
That's kind of a representative
fact of that.

00:22:45.310 --> 00:22:45.720
Yeah?

00:22:45.720 --> 00:22:48.210
AUDIENCE: To some degree, that
variation is to be expected

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:50.202
[INAUDIBLE]

00:22:50.202 --> 00:22:50.700
loan.

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:54.186
So therefore, if it is a smaller
loan, then, of course,

00:22:54.186 --> 00:22:56.710
the percent interest rate
is going to be higher.

00:22:56.710 --> 00:22:57.210
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:22:57.210 --> 00:23:01.215
So to what extent can this be
explained by fixed costs?

00:23:01.215 --> 00:23:02.900
That's the question we'll
ask in a minute.

00:23:02.900 --> 00:23:04.190
I think you're exactly right.

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:05.810
And that goes back
to [INAUDIBLE]

00:23:05.810 --> 00:23:09.200
point earlier, that fixed
costs will play a role.

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:18.870
The issue we are going to ask
is, why is it the case that,

00:23:18.870 --> 00:23:21.310
even if there is a relatively
small fixed cost, that

00:23:21.310 --> 00:23:23.460
translates into such large
differences in

00:23:23.460 --> 00:23:24.620
the interest rate?

00:23:24.620 --> 00:23:25.970
And we're going to see that.

00:23:25.970 --> 00:23:26.770
But you're exactly right.

00:23:26.770 --> 00:23:29.430
That's exactly the intuition
is that it has to be that

00:23:29.430 --> 00:23:31.000
there is some fixed
costs of lending

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:32.250
buried here, somewhere.

00:23:37.950 --> 00:23:40.210
So in that case, there
is this intuition of

00:23:40.210 --> 00:23:43.180
fixed cost we'll explain.

00:23:43.180 --> 00:23:45.300
We also, first, have to explain,
why is it the case

00:23:45.300 --> 00:23:47.110
that the rich borrow more?

00:23:47.110 --> 00:23:48.570
After all, it's not because
you're rich that you

00:23:48.570 --> 00:23:50.410
necessarily have better ideas?

00:23:50.410 --> 00:23:54.810
So to start with, should we take
it as given that the rich

00:23:54.810 --> 00:23:56.520
should be able to borrow more?

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:58.030
In a sense, that's something
that's very intuitive,

00:23:58.030 --> 00:24:03.620
because, here, too, when you
want borrow to pay for you

00:24:03.620 --> 00:24:08.020
house, they're going to ask you
to pay at least 5% of the

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:08.890
value of the house.

00:24:08.890 --> 00:24:11.370
So you can see, immediately,
that the loan you can get is a

00:24:11.370 --> 00:24:13.100
function of how rich you are.

00:24:13.100 --> 00:24:14.550
Or your credit is
also like that.

00:24:14.550 --> 00:24:16.360
They ask you what is your
income, and they give you a

00:24:16.360 --> 00:24:19.550
credit line that sort of
corresponds to your income.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:22.430
But if you think for a few
minutes, in principle, where

00:24:22.430 --> 00:24:24.860
is that coming from.

00:24:24.860 --> 00:24:26.640
That's another thing we kind
of have to understand.

00:24:26.640 --> 00:24:30.830
Does it come from the most basic
model, that the loan you

00:24:30.830 --> 00:24:33.780
can get depends on
how rich you are?

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:35.370
It's not completely obvious.

00:24:35.370 --> 00:24:37.910
And then once we have that, we
need to see, well, does that

00:24:37.910 --> 00:24:40.480
help us explain that the
interest rate also varies with

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:41.960
how rich you are?

00:24:41.960 --> 00:24:43.290
And that's where the
fixed costs are

00:24:43.290 --> 00:24:47.495
going to be very helpful.

00:24:47.495 --> 00:24:48.745
The fifth fact.

00:24:51.230 --> 00:24:53.860
The fact that the rich
pay lower interest

00:24:53.860 --> 00:24:56.020
rates, that's true.

00:24:56.020 --> 00:24:57.670
And that does seem
to be linked to

00:24:57.670 --> 00:24:58.570
how much they borrow.

00:24:58.570 --> 00:25:01.860
The size of the loan is
inversely related to the

00:25:01.860 --> 00:25:02.790
interest rate.

00:25:02.790 --> 00:25:05.320
So that's kind of the same fact
as before, but it's true

00:25:05.320 --> 00:25:06.790
more generally.

00:25:06.790 --> 00:25:11.270
For example, in Udaipur, our
famous district in Rajasthan,

00:25:11.270 --> 00:25:13.280
where we did all of these
studies, we also asked people

00:25:13.280 --> 00:25:15.290
whether they borrow and
how much they pay.

00:25:15.290 --> 00:25:21.380
And basically, the credit for
interest from a loan varied

00:25:21.380 --> 00:25:24.460
for each hectare
that you have.

00:25:24.460 --> 00:25:28.410
Actually, that's not a great
fact to illustrate that.

00:25:28.410 --> 00:25:30.250
But the interest rate
is also declining in

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:32.770
how much you've borrowed.

00:25:32.770 --> 00:25:34.020
So those two are kind
of related.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:39.050
And the sixth fact, which we are
going to need to take into

00:25:39.050 --> 00:25:44.050
account, is that those high
interest rates are going to be

00:25:44.050 --> 00:25:47.880
difficult to explain,
mechanically, by default.

00:25:47.880 --> 00:25:52.050
Because, in fact, people do
not seem to be defaulting.

00:25:52.050 --> 00:25:53.355
Default rates are
very, very low.

00:25:56.680 --> 00:26:02.720
So to summarize, the poor can't

00:26:02.720 --> 00:26:06.060
borrow from formal lenders.

00:26:06.060 --> 00:26:07.620
The interest rates are high.

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:10.140
The interest rates
are variable.

00:26:10.140 --> 00:26:12.410
The rich borrow more.

00:26:12.410 --> 00:26:15.860
People who borrow more pay
lower interest rates.

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:17.930
And the default rates
are very low.

00:26:17.930 --> 00:26:20.380
AUDIENCE: Why would a rich
person borrow from an informal

00:26:20.380 --> 00:26:22.350
lender if they could just
borrow from a bank?

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:24.410
PROFESSOR: Rich meaning
richer.

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:28.550
It doesn't necessarily
mean that they have

00:26:28.550 --> 00:26:31.320
access to the banks.

00:26:31.320 --> 00:26:33.140
So the name of the game--

00:26:33.140 --> 00:26:33.880
yeah, Ben?

00:26:33.880 --> 00:26:36.820
AUDIENCE: Aren't the rates at
the bank higher than the ones

00:26:36.820 --> 00:26:40.740
that the [INAUDIBLE]?

00:26:40.740 --> 00:26:42.810
PROFESSOR: So this is
not in [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:42.810 --> 00:26:44.020
This is in formal lending.

00:26:44.020 --> 00:26:45.940
