So it's not so much more people,
but each person wants

00:54:16.540 --> 00:54:18.650
to run away more.

00:54:18.650 --> 00:54:21.480
So when the interest rate
increases, it makes you run

00:54:21.480 --> 00:54:24.850
away more, which is necessary to
increase the interest rate

00:54:24.850 --> 00:54:27.577
further, which makes you run
away more, et cetera, et

00:54:27.577 --> 00:54:29.470
cetera, up to the point
where it stabilizes.

00:54:29.470 --> 00:54:32.500
And then for some people, it
might never stabilize.

00:54:32.500 --> 00:54:35.340
And these people will not be
able to borrow at all.

00:54:35.340 --> 00:54:41.990
So here you won't be able to
borrow if hw is too small.

00:54:41.990 --> 00:54:46.910
If hw is smaller than
c, you won't borrow.

00:54:46.910 --> 00:54:49.740
The interest rate would
be infinite.

00:54:49.740 --> 00:54:53.460
Because that spiral will
not stabilize.

00:54:53.460 --> 00:54:55.444
For other people, it just
feeds on itself.

00:54:58.610 --> 00:55:06.370
So now this model can explain,
pretty much, all of our facts.

00:55:09.790 --> 00:55:12.840
The poor can't borrow from the
formal lenders, while some

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:15.763
people won't be able
to borrow at all.

00:55:15.763 --> 00:55:19.190
And in particular, people will
be not very able to borrow

00:55:19.190 --> 00:55:24.455
from places which are not able
to impose high costs.

00:55:24.455 --> 00:55:28.270
They are just going to not be
able to borrow to the poor if

00:55:28.270 --> 00:55:30.440
they want to get
the money back.

00:55:30.440 --> 00:55:32.230
The interest rates are high.

00:55:32.230 --> 00:55:37.250
That's because if the cost of
fund is D, the interest rate

00:55:37.250 --> 00:55:38.870
multiplier relative to
that, so you can

00:55:38.870 --> 00:55:40.150
have a big wedge now.

00:55:40.150 --> 00:55:41.710
It's not only the
default rate.

00:55:41.710 --> 00:55:46.200
It's like all this effort that
you have to pay to get people

00:55:46.200 --> 00:55:47.450
to reimburse.

00:55:49.300 --> 00:55:51.840
The interest rates are
very variable.

00:55:51.840 --> 00:55:57.330
And, in part, because, for
example, you know someone a

00:55:57.330 --> 00:55:57.920
little better.

00:55:57.920 --> 00:56:00.700
So that goes back to the
question that was before about

00:56:00.700 --> 00:56:01.480
favoritism.

00:56:01.480 --> 00:56:02.330
Maybe it's favoritism.

00:56:02.330 --> 00:56:03.560
You know them better.

00:56:03.560 --> 00:56:07.150
Well, here, if you know someone
better, you can indeed

00:56:07.150 --> 00:56:10.240
lend them at lower rates,
because knowing someone

00:56:10.240 --> 00:56:14.380
better, maybe, reduces the fixed
cost, c, or maybe it

00:56:14.380 --> 00:56:16.420
increases the cost
of running away.

00:56:16.420 --> 00:56:20.220
All of this will have big
effect, big jump on the

00:56:20.220 --> 00:56:20.830
interest rate.

00:56:20.830 --> 00:56:24.170
So you could have very large
variation in the interest rate

00:56:24.170 --> 00:56:26.570
as a function of this
h and c, et cetera,

00:56:26.570 --> 00:56:27.820
within the same village.

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:34.490
So that's the interests
are variable.

00:56:34.490 --> 00:56:35.970
The rich can borrow more.

00:56:35.970 --> 00:56:38.900
That's because what you can
borrow is a function of how

00:56:38.900 --> 00:56:40.780
much wealth you have.

00:56:40.780 --> 00:56:43.220
And the rich pay lower interest
rates, because they

00:56:43.220 --> 00:56:43.910
borrow more.

00:56:43.910 --> 00:56:45.630
That's because of
the fixed costs.

00:56:45.630 --> 00:56:47.330
And that's good to a point.

00:56:47.330 --> 00:56:49.700
And that's all in equilibrium.

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:51.820
In this model, there are no
defaults, since everything is

00:56:51.820 --> 00:56:54.160
set up to ensure there
is no defaults.

00:56:54.160 --> 00:56:56.340
So the default rates are
nothing but automatic.

00:56:56.340 --> 00:56:59.810
They are the result of
people setting the

00:56:59.810 --> 00:57:01.700
interest rate that way.

00:57:01.700 --> 00:57:06.130
So I think, at an intuition
level, you had seen where this

00:57:06.130 --> 00:57:07.040
was coming.

00:57:07.040 --> 00:57:10.490
But you can see that introducing
these fixed costs,

00:57:10.490 --> 00:57:15.000
plus this proportional cost of
running away helps us kind of

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:16.900
cover, pretty much, all
of our bases in terms

00:57:16.900 --> 00:57:19.540
of the basic facts.

00:57:19.540 --> 00:57:22.320
And then we can go a little bit
further, and we can start

00:57:22.320 --> 00:57:26.920
thinking about other things that
we might try to explain

00:57:26.920 --> 00:57:29.120
with this model.

00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:32.940
So moneylenders are close
to the people.

00:57:32.940 --> 00:57:36.120
So they are the ones who
area able to borrow.

00:57:36.120 --> 00:57:37.840
They are the ones who are
able to punish people.

00:57:37.840 --> 00:57:41.160
They are the ones for which
the fixed cost is lower.

00:57:41.160 --> 00:57:44.300
They may be able
to impose large

00:57:44.300 --> 00:57:47.320
penalties, like the mafia.

00:57:47.320 --> 00:57:51.530
An example we have in the book
is, in India, people called

00:57:51.530 --> 00:57:55.660
Kabuliwala are the moneylenders
or were the

00:57:55.660 --> 00:57:56.770
moneylenders of choice.

00:57:56.770 --> 00:57:58.170
I don't know if they
are still there.

00:57:58.170 --> 00:58:01.370
Kabuliwala, the men from Kabul,
who had this reputation

00:58:01.370 --> 00:58:03.290
of being very fierce.

00:58:03.290 --> 00:58:07.600
So every like Indian child read
the story about the man

00:58:07.600 --> 00:58:12.270
from Kabul, with his tender
heart, but who ends up killing

00:58:12.270 --> 00:58:17.160
someone, because that person
has treated them badly.

00:58:17.160 --> 00:58:20.445
And so you would see a villager
telling this story.

00:58:20.445 --> 00:58:24.670
Or you would see these guys
coming under the pretense of

00:58:24.670 --> 00:58:30.010
selling you dried fruits and,
in fact, being moneylenders.

00:58:30.010 --> 00:58:34.020
Because they are the ones who
you knew that they would be

00:58:34.020 --> 00:58:38.790
able to get at you, with a very
persuasive argument, if

00:58:38.790 --> 00:58:41.151
you were not going to
be able to lend.

00:58:41.151 --> 00:58:43.367
AUDIENCE: I've only read the
article so far, so this might

00:58:43.367 --> 00:58:46.480
be in the book, and I
don't know this yet.

00:58:46.480 --> 00:58:49.532
I was a little curious about
why the banks never work

00:58:49.532 --> 00:58:50.690
directly with these people?

00:58:50.690 --> 00:58:52.180
Is it like a liability thing?

00:58:52.180 --> 00:58:53.206
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:58:53.206 --> 00:59:00.010
So there's an example of that
where Citibank, in India,

00:59:00.010 --> 00:59:02.600
decided that, why wouldn't
they use these guys.

00:59:02.600 --> 00:59:08.290
So they tried to use the kind
of local thugs to repossess

00:59:08.290 --> 00:59:10.280
their car loans.

00:59:10.280 --> 00:59:12.800
But once it got found
out, like they

00:59:12.800 --> 00:59:14.340
ran into big trouble.

00:59:14.340 --> 00:59:19.160
And they had to stop
that operation.

00:59:19.160 --> 00:59:22.950
And it's not clear whether or
not it's welfare increasing to

00:59:22.950 --> 00:59:25.310
forbid Citibank to use
the goondas to

00:59:25.310 --> 00:59:26.690
recover their car loans.

00:59:26.690 --> 00:59:27.500
But they tried.

00:59:27.500 --> 00:59:30.790
And then they ran into problems
with the law.

00:59:30.790 --> 00:59:33.200
So it turns out that it's not
legal to kill people who don't

00:59:33.200 --> 00:59:35.140
reimburse your loan.

00:59:35.140 --> 00:59:38.260
So that was the problem,
exactly.

00:59:38.260 --> 00:59:40.610
That's a good point.

00:59:40.610 --> 00:59:47.220
There is another anecdote in the
book about formal banks--

00:59:47.220 --> 00:59:49.340
I don't remember if
it was Citibank--

00:59:49.340 --> 00:59:53.560
threatening to send
people eunuchs.

00:59:53.560 --> 00:59:57.730
Because, in India, eunuchs
showing their private parts is

00:59:57.730 --> 01:00:03.630
supposed to be like
a bad omen.

01:00:03.630 --> 01:00:07.410
So the thing is, pay up,
or we'll send the

01:00:07.410 --> 01:00:09.495
eunuch to see you.

01:00:09.495 --> 01:00:11.300
AUDIENCE: Did you say, eunuch?

01:00:11.300 --> 01:00:12.290
PROFESSOR: I don't know how--

01:00:12.290 --> 01:00:12.840
eunuchs.

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:14.370
AUDIENCE: You know, eunuch.

01:00:14.370 --> 01:00:17.264
PROFESSOR: Eunuch, eunuchs.

01:00:17.264 --> 01:00:19.195
AUDIENCE: So it's just like
their presence is considered

01:00:19.195 --> 01:00:21.570
like threat in itself?

01:00:21.570 --> 01:00:22.820
PROFESSOR: Their exposition.

01:00:25.460 --> 01:00:27.835
If they expose their
private parts, it's

01:00:27.835 --> 01:00:30.652
supposed to be bad.

01:00:30.652 --> 01:00:33.634
AUDIENCE: Seriously, the banks
were hiring people to flash

01:00:33.634 --> 01:00:35.622
themselves?

01:00:35.622 --> 01:00:37.113
PROFESSOR: Not people,
eunuchs.

01:00:37.113 --> 01:00:40.592
I mean, people who
are eunuchs!

01:00:40.592 --> 01:00:43.077
Not just anybody.

01:00:45.580 --> 01:00:47.205
Not anyone.

01:00:47.205 --> 01:00:48.510
It's a very specialized
industry.

01:00:53.640 --> 01:00:55.480
So that explains why the

01:00:55.480 --> 01:00:57.720
moneylenders have a good business.

01:00:57.720 --> 01:01:01.030
Basically, it's a bit like,
you have to resort to very

01:01:01.030 --> 01:01:01.920
complicated stuff.

01:01:01.920 --> 01:01:04.260
If you're a bank, you
can't threaten to

01:01:04.260 --> 01:01:05.960
kill people, et cetera.

01:01:05.960 --> 01:01:09.180
So the moneylenders
are well placed.

01:01:09.180 --> 01:01:11.780
The problem, however, is that
moneylenders don't have,

01:01:11.780 --> 01:01:15.390
themselves, access to
very cheap funds.

01:01:15.390 --> 01:01:19.720
Because if you have savings,
maybe giving them to a

01:01:19.720 --> 01:01:23.880
moneylender is not the best
thing you can do.

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:27.880
So moneylenders, themselves,
they're cost of fund is high.

01:01:27.880 --> 01:01:30.700
And there is also a multiplier
on the cost of funds, which

01:01:30.700 --> 01:01:32.226
explains why the interest
rates are high.

01:01:34.830 --> 01:01:38.580
So you'd explain why you have a
moneylender doing a good job

01:01:38.580 --> 01:01:40.750
and why their interest
rates are so high.

01:01:40.750 --> 01:01:43.690
So it is not entirely clear,
when you're talking about

01:01:43.690 --> 01:01:48.530
driving them away, that they
are necessarily bad people

01:01:48.530 --> 01:01:50.440
trying to exploit the poor.

01:01:50.440 --> 01:01:53.480
They also have their own cost of
funds that it is expensive.

01:01:53.480 --> 01:01:56.330
And then they are trying to
make a living in this way.

01:01:56.330 --> 01:01:57.324
Yep.

01:01:57.324 --> 01:01:59.312
AUDIENCE: Well, if formal
institutions can't work

01:01:59.312 --> 01:02:02.791
directly with the poor borrowers
and enter that

01:02:02.791 --> 01:02:06.270
interaction, why can't they work
with the moneylenders,

01:02:06.270 --> 01:02:07.761
since those would borrow
larger sums?

01:02:07.761 --> 01:02:13.725
And they could be like a private
person who would just

01:02:13.725 --> 01:02:15.961
decides to borrow from someone
and later decides to do

01:02:15.961 --> 01:02:16.707
something with it.

01:02:16.707 --> 01:02:18.210
Why can't that [INAUDIBLE]?

01:02:18.210 --> 01:02:20.837
PROFESSOR: I think, in a lot
of cases, it's sort of

01:02:20.837 --> 01:02:23.780
happening, which is the
moneylender is like a big

01:02:23.780 --> 01:02:29.140
landlord, who will take
a loan from the bank.

01:02:29.140 --> 01:02:31.540
So I think part of the money
that the moneylender is

01:02:31.540 --> 01:02:34.480
getting is precisely coming
from the bank.

01:02:34.480 --> 01:02:36.780
So that intermediation exists.

01:02:36.780 --> 01:02:39.900
Maybe not be officially,
because moneylending

01:02:39.900 --> 01:02:42.990
is often not legal.

01:02:42.990 --> 01:02:45.770
But they just go and they
borrow some money.

01:02:45.770 --> 01:02:47.258
And then they relend it.

01:02:47.258 --> 01:02:48.512
And that's it.

01:02:48.512 --> 01:02:51.227
AUDIENCE: How do these rates
change with the objective of

01:02:51.227 --> 01:02:54.591
the lending institutions and
the objective of the people

01:02:54.591 --> 01:02:55.769
who are receiving the loans?

01:02:55.769 --> 01:02:59.546
So if there was a social
purpose, as opposed to a

01:02:59.546 --> 01:03:03.784
for-profit purpose, then the
spread would be smaller.

01:03:03.784 --> 01:03:07.053
You'd be trying to break even
versus trying to make some

01:03:07.053 --> 01:03:09.390
income off of the person
you're lending to.

01:03:09.390 --> 01:03:12.300
And I also imagine, if you're
lending to someone who is just

01:03:12.300 --> 01:03:15.050
trying to smooth their
consumption, they'd be more

01:03:15.050 --> 01:03:17.900
likely to pay you back then if
you were lending to someone

01:03:17.900 --> 01:03:20.530
who was trying to start a
business then, who's success

01:03:20.530 --> 01:03:22.380
rate might also be low.

01:03:22.380 --> 01:03:25.255
PROFESSOR: So in this particular
model, we have

01:03:25.255 --> 01:03:26.550
assumed-- and, in fact,
I'm going to come back

01:03:26.550 --> 01:03:28.010
to that in a moment--

01:03:28.010 --> 01:03:29.670
that there is perfect
competition between

01:03:29.670 --> 01:03:31.880
moneylenders.

01:03:31.880 --> 01:03:34.650
So people, are here,
breaking even.

01:03:34.650 --> 01:03:38.060
So in that sense, you can't do
better from that without

01:03:38.060 --> 01:03:39.110
starting to lose money.

01:03:39.110 --> 01:03:42.800
However, you're exactly right
that someone could decide that

01:03:42.800 --> 01:03:45.940
it is worthwhile for them
subsidize the interest rate.

01:03:45.940 --> 01:03:49.020
For example, you are
like an NGO.

01:03:49.020 --> 01:03:51.430
And you want to do something
good for the poor.

01:03:51.430 --> 01:03:54.210
You could decide that you're
going to want to subsidize the

01:03:54.210 --> 01:03:56.140
interest rate, a bit.

01:03:56.140 --> 01:04:00.955
And then you're going to benefit
from the multiplier

01:04:00.955 --> 01:04:03.440
rate the other way.

01:04:03.440 --> 01:04:09.080
So if you were good at it, if
someone had the local presence

01:04:09.080 --> 01:04:11.570
and were able to replicate
what the moneylenders are

01:04:11.570 --> 01:04:16.000
doing, in terms of lowering the
rate of running away with

01:04:16.000 --> 01:04:18.870
the money and lowering the fixed
cost of lending, and

01:04:18.870 --> 01:04:21.400
they combined that with some
subsidies of the interest

01:04:21.400 --> 01:04:26.750
rate, then the multiplier would
play in your favor.

01:04:26.750 --> 01:04:31.370
And that's where the microcredit
comes in.

01:04:31.370 --> 01:04:36.530
When we talk about microcredit,
in a way, they

01:04:36.530 --> 01:04:39.510
are still, say, trying
to break even.

01:04:39.510 --> 01:04:42.850
Or they might even be willing to
lose a little bit of money.

01:04:42.850 --> 01:04:45.370
And this losing a little bit of
money might translate into

01:04:45.370 --> 01:04:47.700
a large drop in the
interest rate.

01:04:47.700 --> 01:04:48.410
You're exactly right.

01:04:48.410 --> 01:04:51.820
If you're willing to, any profit
that you're going to

01:04:51.820 --> 01:04:56.970
give away might translate into a
lot of money saved, from the

01:04:56.970 --> 01:04:58.570
point of view of the lender.

01:04:58.570 --> 01:05:02.560
You're also right on the other
end, which is all of these

01:05:02.560 --> 01:05:04.900
things depend on the propensity
of people to run

01:05:04.900 --> 01:05:05.880
away and things like that.

01:05:05.880 --> 01:05:08.490
If you could identify good
borrowers that are not going

01:05:08.490 --> 01:05:13.030
to default, they are borrowers
with a big h, in a sense.

01:05:13.030 --> 01:05:14.960
And there are borrowers
you could lend to

01:05:14.960 --> 01:05:17.210
with a lower rate.

01:05:17.210 --> 01:05:19.830
The problem is, for the
moneylender or for the bank,

01:05:19.830 --> 01:05:22.170
is whether they can identify
people with a low

01:05:22.170 --> 01:05:24.472
or high h or not.

01:05:30.350 --> 01:05:33.560
In this world, you would
have what you see with

01:05:33.560 --> 01:05:36.070
moneylenders, which is
moneylenders that charge very

01:05:36.070 --> 01:05:38.820
high rates, get very low
defaults, in equilibrium, they

01:05:38.820 --> 01:05:42.140
don't need to break anybody's
kneecap, as long as it's known

01:05:42.140 --> 01:05:44.630
that that's what would happen.

01:05:48.030 --> 01:05:51.550
Another story about the
moneylenders, however, is that

01:05:51.550 --> 01:05:58.720
it is not that they just have to
charge this high rates and

01:05:58.720 --> 01:06:02.330
variable rates because of the
fixed cost of lending and

01:06:02.330 --> 01:06:05.230
monitoring the loans,
but because they

01:06:05.230 --> 01:06:07.850
are monopoly lenders.

01:06:07.850 --> 01:06:11.560
So that's another thing that you
often hear is that these

01:06:11.560 --> 01:06:16.560
guys, it's one game in
town in the village.

01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:20.430
They are the only one who can
lend the money to you.

01:06:20.430 --> 01:06:22.890
And therefore, they are just
charging you this huge rate,

01:06:22.890 --> 01:06:27.060
just because they are the
only possibility.

01:06:27.060 --> 01:06:32.380
And you have two facts
when trying to

01:06:32.380 --> 01:06:33.700
evaluate these claims.

01:06:33.700 --> 01:06:36.220
You have two facts which are
pulling in slightly different

01:06:36.220 --> 01:06:37.580
directions.

01:06:37.580 --> 01:06:40.640
One fact is that, usually, in a
village, you have more than

01:06:40.640 --> 01:06:42.270
one moneylender.

01:06:42.270 --> 01:06:44.580
You could have at least like
four or five moneylenders,

01:06:44.580 --> 01:06:47.730
which are like the shopkeeper
and then the guy

01:06:47.730 --> 01:06:50.170
who has a big land.

01:06:50.170 --> 01:06:54.060
And two or three people like
that will be moneylenders.

01:06:54.060 --> 01:06:57.580
So in principle, there is
competition between them.

01:06:57.580 --> 01:07:02.420
However, you don't see
people switching.

01:07:02.420 --> 01:07:06.120
So people usually stick
to the same person.

01:07:06.120 --> 01:07:10.190
So it is not clear in the end.

01:07:10.190 --> 01:07:13.550
Is it a competitive situation,
because, in principle, you

01:07:13.550 --> 01:07:14.790
have a choice?

01:07:14.790 --> 01:07:17.640
Or is it a monopoly situation,
because, in practice, you

01:07:17.640 --> 01:07:19.430
don't switch?

01:07:19.430 --> 01:07:23.120
So what's your view of how we
can try and explain that, by

01:07:23.120 --> 01:07:24.900
just enriching this
model just a bit?

01:07:33.648 --> 01:07:36.078
AUDIENCE: Well, I'm not sure how
to incorporate this, but I

01:07:36.078 --> 01:07:37.050
can think of two facts.

01:07:37.050 --> 01:07:41.106
First, the person who borrows
needs to have some trust for

01:07:41.106 --> 01:07:45.552
the moneylender, in the sense
of like the moneylender says

01:07:45.552 --> 01:07:48.516
you have to pay this interest
rate and then doesn't raise it

01:07:48.516 --> 01:07:50.986
immediately when you actually
go to repay.

01:07:50.986 --> 01:07:53.456
And that requires some costs
to establish this

01:07:53.456 --> 01:07:53.950
relationship.

01:07:53.950 --> 01:07:57.408
Then there's also some cost to
switching, again, to establish

01:07:57.408 --> 01:07:58.890
this relationship with
another moneylender.

01:07:58.890 --> 01:08:01.456
But there might be the trade-off
that you hear, from

01:08:01.456 --> 01:08:03.151
other people, that the other
moneylender charges

01:08:03.151 --> 01:08:05.960
significantly lower rates
or something like that.

01:08:05.960 --> 01:08:06.970
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:08:06.970 --> 01:08:09.490
So if evaluate on the cost
of switching-- yeah?

01:08:09.490 --> 01:08:12.168
AUDIENCE: Didn't you also say
that the c would decrease if

01:08:12.168 --> 01:08:13.386
you stayed with the
same moneylender?

01:08:13.386 --> 01:08:16.308
Because they don't need
to recheck you out.

01:08:16.308 --> 01:08:19.230
So in the future, they can
charge you the lower rate

01:08:19.230 --> 01:08:21.670
because of this.

01:08:21.670 --> 01:08:21.830
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:08:21.830 --> 01:08:22.992
So there could be.

01:08:22.992 --> 01:08:26.970
You see, this cost of switching,
part of it is the

01:08:26.970 --> 01:08:29.310
guy trying to figure
out who you are.

01:08:29.310 --> 01:08:33.990
So we can think a part of
the c as being paid

01:08:33.990 --> 01:08:34.950
once and for all.

01:08:34.950 --> 01:08:37.790
And then maybe you're paying c
again every time you borrow.

01:08:37.790 --> 01:08:42.439
But a part of the c might be,
maybe, paid once and for all.

01:08:42.439 --> 01:08:50.210
Now, it means that, if you want
to switch, you would need

01:08:50.210 --> 01:08:53.300
pay this c again.

01:08:53.300 --> 01:08:56.290
So number one, that would mean
that you would pay a higher

01:08:56.290 --> 01:08:57.310
interest rate.

01:08:57.310 --> 01:09:01.939
Number two, on the other hand,
the lender, to whom you are

01:09:01.939 --> 01:09:05.029
coming, he's going to wonder
about, why is it

01:09:05.029 --> 01:09:06.789
that they are switching?

01:09:10.990 --> 01:09:14.260
If the c has been paid, once and
for all, you should want

01:09:14.260 --> 01:09:16.300
to stay with your moneylender.

01:09:16.300 --> 01:09:19.880
If you're not, it might mean
that you have something

01:09:19.880 --> 01:09:22.410
suspicious about you.

01:09:22.410 --> 01:09:26.109
So here, in this model, we have
only included a moral

01:09:26.109 --> 01:09:28.950
hazard that is the probability
of running

01:09:28.950 --> 01:09:30.520
away with the money.

01:09:30.520 --> 01:09:33.910
But there could be an element
of adverse selection.

01:09:33.910 --> 01:09:37.810
There could be some people who
are more likely to run away or

01:09:37.810 --> 01:09:39.029
less likely to run away.

01:09:39.029 --> 01:09:42.189
And you just don't
know as a lender.

01:09:42.189 --> 01:09:44.189
And you need to investigate.

01:09:44.189 --> 01:09:47.720
Now, if you're trying to
switch from an existing

01:09:47.720 --> 01:09:51.550
lender, lending relationship,
which, in principle, gives you

01:09:51.550 --> 01:09:55.880
these lower rates, it might be
because you have something to

01:09:55.880 --> 01:09:58.270
hide about what your cost is.

01:09:58.270 --> 01:10:02.780
So the resenting moneylender is
going to think that you are

01:10:02.780 --> 01:10:05.100
a high risk kind of a guy.

01:10:05.100 --> 01:10:07.350
So he's either going to spend
even more effort checking you

01:10:07.350 --> 01:10:10.425
out, or he's going to charge you
higher rate and lend you

01:10:10.425 --> 01:10:15.210
less money to correspond to
the most risky people.

01:10:15.210 --> 01:10:20.160
So because of that, the fact
that you are switching,

01:10:20.160 --> 01:10:23.830
because it might signal that
you're a bad type, makes it

01:10:23.830 --> 01:10:26.570
even less likely that
you'll switch.

01:10:26.570 --> 01:10:31.920
So if we add a layer of like
adverse selection.

01:10:31.920 --> 01:10:34.240
You know about yourself
than the lender

01:10:34.240 --> 01:10:36.420
knows, which is realistic.

01:10:36.420 --> 01:10:40.450
Then that will make switching
unlikely.

01:10:40.450 --> 01:10:44.040
That means that you're stuck in
your existing relationship,

01:10:44.040 --> 01:10:49.120
which means that the lender will
try to exploit the fact

01:10:49.120 --> 01:10:51.580
that you're stuck into this
existing relationship.

01:10:51.580 --> 01:10:55.990
He will say, well, staying with
me brings you a surplus.

01:10:55.990 --> 01:10:59.670
I'm going to extract some of
that surplus from you, which

01:10:59.670 --> 01:11:01.910
means that, even though there
is a lot of competition,

01:11:01.910 --> 01:11:05.140
ex-ante, ex-post, you might
be stuck in a one on one

01:11:05.140 --> 01:11:06.890
exploitative relationship.

01:11:06.890 --> 01:11:08.730
So that's why we can have
these kind of two things

01:11:08.730 --> 01:11:11.310
together, of a lot of
competition and, at the same

01:11:11.310 --> 01:11:14.240
time, this one on one monopoly
relationship.

01:11:14.240 --> 01:11:14.670
Yeah?

01:11:14.670 --> 01:11:16.390
AUDIENCE: For all this to hold
true, it must be true that

01:11:16.390 --> 01:11:17.620
rates that the different
moneylenders

01:11:17.620 --> 01:11:19.230
charge are about equal.

01:11:19.230 --> 01:11:22.025
Because if there was a huge
benefit to switching, it might

01:11:22.025 --> 01:11:23.260
out weigh the costs.

01:11:23.260 --> 01:11:23.605
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:11:23.605 --> 01:11:27.210
So it's to a point, it's
going to equilibriate.

01:11:27.210 --> 01:11:30.480
So basically, what the
moneylender that your are with

01:11:30.480 --> 01:11:33.290
is going to do is that they are
going to set the interest

01:11:33.290 --> 01:11:38.660
rate just low enough that
switching is not worth it.

01:11:38.660 --> 01:11:43.070
But that means they are going
to start making a profit on

01:11:43.070 --> 01:11:45.680
the people in which they
have a relationship.

01:11:45.680 --> 01:11:50.640
Because now, they know that they
can do better than just

01:11:50.640 --> 01:11:52.310
charging the break even rate.

01:11:52.310 --> 01:11:56.980
Because there is this gain of
thing with them, which is a

01:11:56.980 --> 01:11:57.950
very big gain.

01:11:57.950 --> 01:12:02.720
Because the other people would
be quite suspicious of you.

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:04.050
And you're exactly right.

01:12:04.050 --> 01:12:07.000
Everybody will end up charging
the same rates in a village,

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.100
in equilibrium.

01:12:08.100 --> 01:12:11.040
And this rate will be higher
than the rate that they would

01:12:11.040 --> 01:12:14.620
have been charging in
the absence of this

01:12:14.620 --> 01:12:15.870
difficulty to switch.

01:12:19.260 --> 01:12:24.215
So that's why you could have
like this combination of, you

01:12:24.215 --> 01:12:26.420
know, they are kind of running
their business in a difficult

01:12:26.420 --> 01:12:29.220
situation, and they are actually
taking advantage of

01:12:29.220 --> 01:12:29.760
their clients.

01:12:29.760 --> 01:12:30.248
Yeah?

01:12:30.248 --> 01:12:32.200
AUDIENCE: I know that one of
the articles that I read--

01:12:32.200 --> 01:12:35.616
I think it was [INAUDIBLE]
professor that proposed it or

01:12:35.616 --> 01:12:38.560
proposed-- or maybe it was
the Finacial Times--

01:12:38.560 --> 01:12:42.054
creating this central--
at least in India--

01:12:42.054 --> 01:12:46.615
MFI, like a database of all the
loans, of some way to see

01:12:46.615 --> 01:12:49.390
everybody's indebtedness,
across the board.

01:12:49.390 --> 01:12:52.670
Wouldn't this help minimize
the cost of switching?

01:12:52.670 --> 01:12:55.370
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:12:55.370 --> 01:12:58.810
This kind of central database,
credit registry, similar to

01:12:58.810 --> 01:13:01.450
what we have in the US,
that would help.

01:13:01.450 --> 01:13:04.910
Because that would exactly
solve this problem.

01:13:04.910 --> 01:13:07.350
Because then the new moneylender
would know exactly

01:13:07.350 --> 01:13:08.430
what is your history.

01:13:08.430 --> 01:13:09.790
The thing is the moneylenders
are not going

01:13:09.790 --> 01:13:11.150
to enter into that.

01:13:11.150 --> 01:13:15.100
So that is something that the
microfinance agencies could do

01:13:15.100 --> 01:13:16.340
for themselves.

01:13:16.340 --> 01:13:20.250
But that's something that
moneylenders won't do.

01:13:20.250 --> 01:13:22.390
There is sort of one more fact
that is going to push the

01:13:22.390 --> 01:13:26.680
interest rate up that is less
benevolent from the point of

01:13:26.680 --> 01:13:27.930
view of the moneylender.

01:13:33.090 --> 01:13:35.770
The formal institution
we already discussed.

01:13:35.770 --> 01:13:38.450
The formal institutions
are far away.

01:13:38.450 --> 01:13:40.540
The formal institutions
don't have a

01:13:40.540 --> 01:13:43.690
means to threaten people.

01:13:43.690 --> 01:13:51.030
The formal institutions, even
if they were able to get

01:13:51.030 --> 01:13:54.770
people to repay, they might not
like headlines of farmer's

01:13:54.770 --> 01:13:56.350
suicide and all that.

01:13:56.350 --> 01:13:58.590
So that doesn't put them
in a very favorable

01:13:58.590 --> 01:14:03.100
situation to lend.

01:14:03.100 --> 01:14:08.800
So these difficulties in the
credit market explain why,

01:14:08.800 --> 01:14:13.310
despite the effort, the formal
institutions have been

01:14:13.310 --> 01:14:19.450
relatively unable to lend to the
poor until now and explain

01:14:19.450 --> 01:14:22.630
why people have access to all of
these moneylenders at these

01:14:22.630 --> 01:14:24.320
very high rates.

01:14:24.320 --> 01:14:28.210
The genius of microcredit is to
introduce an institutional

01:14:28.210 --> 01:14:32.060
form that solves a lot of
these problems without

01:14:32.060 --> 01:14:35.350
resorting to breaking
people's kneecaps.

01:14:35.350 --> 01:14:38.270
So what microfinance does-- and
you're going to see that

01:14:38.270 --> 01:14:40.070
in much more detail next week.

01:14:42.920 --> 01:14:44.870
What are the key elements of
the model of microfinance?

01:14:47.624 --> 01:14:50.079
AUDIENCE: You borrow in
groups, [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:53.030 --> 01:14:54.390
PROFESSOR: And what is
the group doing?

01:14:54.390 --> 01:14:55.990
What is the value
of the group?

01:14:55.990 --> 01:14:57.900
See, if we put it in the context
of the model, what is

01:14:57.900 --> 01:14:59.210
the value of the group?

01:14:59.210 --> 01:15:02.268
AUDIENCE: So they insure
payment for each other.

01:15:02.268 --> 01:15:05.130
So if one person defaults, the
others can cover the loan.

01:15:05.130 --> 01:15:05.610
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:15:05.610 --> 01:15:08.014
So where does it play out in
normal debt, in term of the

01:15:08.014 --> 01:15:08.610
parameters?

01:15:08.610 --> 01:15:11.070
AUDIENCE: It decreases
the run away risk.

01:15:11.070 --> 01:15:13.830
PROFESSOR: It decreases
the run away risk.

01:15:13.830 --> 01:15:15.656
It could also decrease the fixed
cost, because you know

01:15:15.656 --> 01:15:16.780
people are not running away.

01:15:16.780 --> 01:15:20.480
The cost of the monitoring, it's
not that it decreases .

01:15:20.480 --> 01:15:22.950
Someone still needs to pay
for the monitoring.

01:15:22.950 --> 01:15:24.240
But it is the other people.

01:15:24.240 --> 01:15:25.950
It's not the bank anymore.

01:15:25.950 --> 01:15:28.270
So there is no multiplier.

01:15:28.270 --> 01:15:30.090
The cost of the monitoring
reduces.

01:15:30.090 --> 01:15:33.480
And therefore, because of the
multiplier effect, you can

01:15:33.480 --> 01:15:36.460
reduce the interest rate quite
a bit as a function of that.

01:15:36.460 --> 01:15:39.170
So that's one, group lending.

01:15:39.170 --> 01:15:43.175
What else is microcredit
doing?

01:15:43.175 --> 01:15:45.610
AUDIENCE: I know two of the
functions they have, like

01:15:45.610 --> 01:15:47.558
certain payment schedules
and steps.

01:15:47.558 --> 01:15:51.210
And typically, they assign you
some sort of consultant or

01:15:51.210 --> 01:15:54.619
someone who helps you discuss
business plans

01:15:54.619 --> 01:15:55.350
and stuff like that.

01:15:55.350 --> 01:15:58.050
So your default risk is also
lower, because you'll make

01:15:58.050 --> 01:15:59.780
smarter use of it.

01:15:59.780 --> 01:16:00.190
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:16:00.190 --> 01:16:03.130
So they can reduce the default
rate like that.

01:16:03.130 --> 01:16:06.070
The other thing you said is
that they have this very

01:16:06.070 --> 01:16:07.700
regular schedule.

01:16:07.700 --> 01:16:10.680
So they try and reduce the
administrative cost by making

01:16:10.680 --> 01:16:12.920
all of the products the same.

01:16:12.920 --> 01:16:15.410
So the typical microcredit loan
is you take a loan, and

01:16:15.410 --> 01:16:19.660
then you reimburse it in 52
installments of the same size.

01:16:19.660 --> 01:16:25.000
So that means one guy can
handle a vast number of

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:28.290
repayments in just one round.

01:16:28.290 --> 01:16:30.990
They basically go from village
to village, meet with the

01:16:30.990 --> 01:16:33.800
entire center, which is usually
a combination of these

01:16:33.800 --> 01:16:36.610
groups, and take all the
money at once and go.

01:16:36.610 --> 01:16:40.040
And so that reduces the c, if
you want, the cost, the fixed

01:16:40.040 --> 01:16:42.320
cost of administering the loan,
which, again, can be

01:16:42.320 --> 01:16:45.890
passed to the borrower.

01:16:45.890 --> 01:16:48.746
AUDIENCE: As a result of that
as well, you're making a

01:16:48.746 --> 01:16:53.520
relationship with
the borrower.

01:16:53.520 --> 01:16:56.889
You build a relationship of
trust and the incentive is to

01:16:56.889 --> 01:17:00.638
want to pay back [INAUDIBLE].

01:17:00.638 --> 01:17:04.550
PROFESSOR: Right, another thing
that microfinance has is

01:17:04.550 --> 01:17:08.830
that they are lending one loan,
that's usually small at

01:17:08.830 --> 01:17:10.820
the beginning, and then they
increase it and then they

01:17:10.820 --> 01:17:12.650
increase it and then
they increase it.

01:17:12.650 --> 01:17:14.440
And that's supposed to
give people incentive

01:17:14.440 --> 01:17:15.840
to continue to repay.

01:17:15.840 --> 01:17:18.800
Although one has to wonder
when that stops.

01:17:18.800 --> 01:17:20.510
Because, eventually, they might
consider that they have

01:17:20.510 --> 01:17:22.830
now built up enough that they
can just default with the

01:17:22.830 --> 01:17:24.070
entire money.

01:17:24.070 --> 01:17:28.290
But over the whole beginning of
relationship, you are going

01:17:28.290 --> 01:17:31.930
to benefit from this incentive
to continue repaying.

01:17:31.930 --> 01:17:34.180
Because now the incentive is
not only I'm going to break

01:17:34.180 --> 01:17:36.410
your kneecap if you don't repay,
but it's I'm not going

01:17:36.410 --> 01:17:39.980
to lend you another loan.

01:17:39.980 --> 01:17:46.440
So making product very
standardized makes it to

01:17:46.440 --> 01:17:49.800
available to hire people, who
are less well known, going

01:17:49.800 --> 01:17:51.990
straight to the villages,
using the group loans.

01:17:51.990 --> 01:17:55.840
All of that reduces the cost of
lending, which, because of

01:17:55.840 --> 01:17:57.480
the multiplier, is passed
to interest.

01:17:57.480 --> 01:18:00.800
And of course, they are often
nonprofit or even subsidized,

01:18:00.800 --> 01:18:03.360
which again helps, with
regard with the

01:18:03.360 --> 01:18:05.720
discussion we had before.

01:18:05.720 --> 01:18:07.190
So I'm going to leave
it here for now.

01:18:07.190 --> 01:18:10.120
And then, next time, we're going
to get much more into

01:18:10.120 --> 01:18:11.370
detail about microcredit.